msDesc.head: Accounts of properties of the hospital in Vernon

supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in ink and pencil.

p.note: Top of page, in black ink by a medieval hand, four lines of text in French; bottom left corner, National Library book label with current signum.

binding.p: Medieval binding. Brown leather over wooden boards. 4 double raised bands, 2 single raised band, and endbands. , top of page in black ink: No 39. Reditus Domus Dei in vernone. , black ink and printed on a torn label: St-s II REDITUS DOMUS DEI DE VERNONE; stamped in gold (but faded): A 239; National Library book label with current signum.
binding.condition: Leather worn. repaired with newer leather. , repairs with white leather; middle of cover outer edge, 2 holes; upper part of cover, two nails (remnats of clasp).

history.provenance: The manuscript was likely written in Vernon. Later the manuscript probably belonged to Paul Petau, from whom it was acquired by Queen Christina and brought to Sweden. The signum on the corresponds to the catalogue of 1734 (125e), where it is listed as: Phil. in 4o no 39.
In the manuscript was on loan to Vernon.

note.p: The manuscript contains many blank leaves to allow the list to be expanded. These leaves are ruled and sometimes provided with running titles.

supportDesc.condition: , : bottom half of leaf cut off.

layout.note: Ruling in ink and lead. Pricking (slahes) in the margins. The majority of the text is a list. The top most line is used for the running titles, the outer margin is ruled in several narrow columns. One of these columns is filled with roman numerals and in the column next to the main text the capitals introducing a new paragraph is placed.

p.note: Elaborate cross-like shape drawn in the outer margin in brown ink.
Additions in the margin in ink by a medieval hand. The first two are short additions, while the one on is longer (8 lines).
Parchemnt note attahced to with a metal pin. contain 7 lines of text in French written by a medieval hand, is blank.

decoDesc.p: Main text in black ink. Capitals often placed in a separate column in the outer margin, e.g. .
